<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Context Debt Report — promptc</title>
  <style>{{ styles | safe }}</style>
</head>
<body>

  <main>

    {% if scan.cursor_sibling_files %}
    <div class="cursor-warning">
      Detected <code>.cursor/rules/</code>
      ({{ scan.cursor_sibling_files }} file{{ '' if scan.cursor_sibling_files == 1 else 's' }})
      — not yet scanned. Cursor support is tracked for v0.2.
    </div>
    {% endif %}

    {% if hero_state == "insufficient" %}
    <section class="hero hero--insufficient">
      <div class="hero__eyebrow">NOT ENOUGH TO AUDIT YET</div>
      <p class="hero__copy">
        Your <code>.claude/</code> has {{ skill_count }}
        skill file{{ '' if skill_count == 1 else 's' }}
        ({{ "{:,}".format(scan.skill_body_tokens) }} body tokens).
      </p>
      <p class="hero__copy hero__copy--dim">
        promptc currently audits <code>.claude/</code> only — if your prompts
        live in <code>.cursor/rules/</code>, support is tracked for v0.2.
      </p>
      <p class="hero__copy hero__copy--dim">
        promptc needs at least 3 skills and 1,000 body tokens to find
        patterns. Add more skills, or point promptc at a larger directory.
      </p>
    </section>

    {% elif hero_state == "debt" %}
    <section class="hero hero--{{ grade.letter | lower }}">
      <div class="hero__grade-wrap">
        <span class="hero__grade-label">Grade</span>
        <span class="hero__grade-value">{{ grade.display }}</span>
      </div>

      <div class="hero__primary">
        <div class="hero__number">{{ "{:,}".format(dedup.total_wasted_tokens) }}</div>
        <div class="hero__number-label">
          tokens of duplicate content across
          {{ dedup.per_file_wasted | length }} file{{ '' if dedup.per_file_wasted | length == 1 else 's' }}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="hero__secondary">
        ({{ "{:.0%}".format(grade.bloat_ratio) }} of {{ "{:,}".format(body_total_tokens) }} body tokens)
      </div>

      {% if exposure.multiplier and exposure.multiplier > 1 %}
      <div class="hero__amplifier">
        Plus
        <strong>{{ "{:.1f}×".format(exposure.multiplier) }}</strong>
        worst-case context exposure on top.
      </div>
      {% endif %}

      <div class="hero__pointer">Top offenders below ↓</div>
    </section>

    {% else %}
    {# clean / moderate state — A or B/C, no multiplier in hero #}
    <section class="hero hero--{{ grade.letter | lower }}">
      <div class="hero__grade-wrap">
        <span class="hero__grade-label">Grade</span>
        <span class="hero__grade-value">{{ grade.display }}</span>
      </div>

      {% if grade.letter == "A" %}
        {% if dedup.total_groups == 0 %}
      <p class="hero__headline">Your <code>.claude/</code> is clean.</p>
      <p class="hero__copy hero__copy--dim">
        No duplicate content found.
        {{ skills_with_description }} of {{ skill_count }}
        skill{{ '' if skill_count == 1 else 's' }} have descriptions.
      </p>
        {% else %}
      <p class="hero__headline">
        Mostly clean — {{ dedup.total_groups }}
        small duplicate group{{ '' if dedup.total_groups == 1 else 's' }} flagged below.
      </p>
      <p class="hero__copy hero__copy--dim">
        {{ skills_with_description }} of {{ skill_count }}
        skill{{ '' if skill_count == 1 else 's' }} have descriptions.
      </p>
        {% endif %}
      {% else %}
      <p class="hero__headline">
        {{ dedup.total_groups }} duplicate
        group{{ '' if dedup.total_groups == 1 else 's' }} found
        ({{ "{:,}".format(dedup.total_wasted_tokens) }} tokens,
        {{ "{:.0%}".format(grade.bloat_ratio) }} of body).
      </p>
      <p class="hero__copy hero__copy--dim">
        {{ skill_count }} skill file{{ '' if skill_count == 1 else 's' }} scanned.
      </p>
      {% endif %}

      <p class="hero__pointer">
        See <em>Skill Context Exposure</em> below for worst-case load detail.
      </p>
    </section>
    {% endif %}

    {% if hero_state != "insufficient" %}
    <p class="hero-disclaimer">
      Token counts via OpenAI's <code>cl100k_base</code> as a Claude
      tokenizer proxy. Grade thresholds are heuristics. See
      <a href="#methodology">how this is graded</a> for full caveats.
    </p>
    {% endif %}

    {% if exposure.skill_count and exposure.multiplier and not scan.is_insufficient %}
    <section class="card exposure">
      <header class="card__header">
        <h2>Skill Context Exposure</h2>
        <p class="card__subtitle">Worst-case context cost if a SKILL.md body
        ends up in context instead of just its description.</p>
      </header>

      <div class="exposure__grid">
        <div class="exposure__cell">
          <div class="exposure__label">Promised load</div>
          <div class="exposure__value">{{ "{:,}".format(exposure.total_promised) }}</div>
          <div class="exposure__hint">description tokens</div>
        </div>
        <div class="exposure__cell exposure__cell--worst">
          <div class="exposure__label">Worst-case load</div>
          <div class="exposure__value">{{ "{:,}".format(exposure.total_worst_case) }}</div>
          <div class="exposure__hint">SKILL.md body tokens</div>
        </div>
        <div class="exposure__cell exposure__cell--mult">
          <div class="exposure__label">Exposure multiplier</div>
          <div class="exposure__value exposure__value--mult">{{ "{:.1f}×".format(exposure.multiplier) }}</div>
          <div class="exposure__hint">body ÷ description</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      {% set max_load = exposure.total_worst_case if exposure.total_worst_case else 1 %}
      <div class="exposure__bars">
        <div class="exposure__bar-row">
          <span class="exposure__bar-label">Promised</span>
          <div class="exposure__bar-track">
            <div class="exposure__bar-fill exposure__bar-fill--promised"
                 style="width: {{ (exposure.total_promised / max_load * 100) | round(2) }}%;"></div>
          </div>
          <span class="exposure__bar-num">{{ "{:,}".format(exposure.total_promised) }}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="exposure__bar-row">
          <span class="exposure__bar-label">Worst case</span>
          <div class="exposure__bar-track">
            <div class="exposure__bar-fill exposure__bar-fill--worst"
                 style="width: 100%;"></div>
          </div>
          <span class="exposure__bar-num">{{ "{:,}".format(exposure.total_worst_case) }}</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      {% if exposure.files %}
      <h3 class="exposure__subhead">Top skills by worst-case load</h3>
      <table class="files exposure__top">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="col-path">Skill</th>
            <th class="col-num">Worst-case</th>
            <th class="col-num">Promised</th>
            <th class="col-num">Mult.</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {% for f in exposure.files[:5] %}
          <tr>
            <td class="col-path"><code>{{ f.file_path }}</code></td>
            <td class="col-num">{{ "{:,}".format(f.worst_case_tokens) }}</td>
            <td class="col-num">{{ "{:,}".format(f.promised_tokens) }}</td>
            <td class="col-num">
              {% if f.multiplier %}
                <strong>{{ "{:.1f}×".format(f.multiplier) }}</strong>
              {% else %}
                <span class="dim">n/a</span>
              {% endif %}
            </td>
          </tr>
          {% endfor %}
        </tbody>
      </table>
      {% endif %}

      {% if exposure.skills_without_description %}
      <p class="callout">
        <strong>{{ exposure.skills_without_description | length }} skill(s) have no description field.</strong>
        Their promised load is 0, so there is no startup metadata to match
        against; the full body is the only way to know what they do.
      </p>
      {% endif %}

      <div class="exposure__sources">
        <p>Claude Code's Skills documentation describes the loading
        model: skill descriptions load into context at session start so
        Claude knows what's available, while the full SKILL.md body
        loads only when the skill is invoked.</p>
        <ul class="exposure__links">
          <li>Docs:
            <a href="{{ anthropic_docs_url }}" rel="noopener">{{ anthropic_docs_url }}</a>
          </li>
          <li>Community report of body loading anyway:
            <a href="{{ community_issue_url }}" rel="noopener">{{ community_issue_url }}</a>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="exposure__disclaimer">The multiplier above is the ceiling of
        your exposure if the full body ends up in context. This tool makes
        no claim about whether that happens in your setup; it measures
        the upper bound.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
    {% endif %}

    {% if top_duplicates %}
    <section class="card">
      <header class="card__header">
        <h2>Duplicate rules ({{ dedup.total_groups }} group{{ '' if dedup.total_groups == 1 else 's' }})</h2>
        <p class="card__subtitle">Top {{ top_duplicates | length }} group(s) by
        duplicate-token count. The canonical chunk (longest version) is highlighted; the
        other chunks are what promptc would consider redundant.
        {% if dedup.language_variant_groups %}
        Groups tagged <em>language variant</em> are per-binding SDK / language
        documentation copies — surfaced for visibility, but excluded from the
        Grade.
        {% endif %}
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="dups">
        {% for group in top_duplicates %}
        <article class="dup">
          <header class="dup__header">
            <span class="dup__rank">#{{ group.rank }}</span>
            <span class="dup__kind dup__kind--{{ group.kind }}"
                  title="{% if group.kind == 'exact' %}All chunks normalize to the same string after stripping markdown.{% else %}At least 0.85 Jaccard similarity on word sets after normalization.{% endif %}">{{ group.kind }}</span>
            {% if group.is_language_variant %}
            <span class="dup__variant"
                  title="Cluster paths differ only in known language segments (e.g. /python/ vs /go/) — treated as legitimate per-binding documentation, not bloat. Excluded from the Grade.">language variant</span>
            {% endif %}
            <span class="dup__wasted">
              {% if group.is_language_variant %}
              {{ "{:,}".format(group.wasted_tokens) }} tokens of repeated content
              {% else %}
              {{ "{:,}".format(group.wasted_tokens) }} duplicate tokens
              {% endif %}
            </span>
            <span class="dup__count dim">{{ group.size }} chunks</span>
          </header>
          <div class="dup__chunks">
            {% for chunk in group.chunks %}
            <div class="dup__chunk{% if chunk.is_canonical %} dup__chunk--canonical{% endif %}">
              <div class="dup__chunk-meta">
                <code class="dup__chunk-path">{{ chunk.file_path }}</code>
                <span class="dim">chunk {{ chunk.chunk_index }} · {{ "{:,}".format(chunk.tokens) }} tokens</span>
                {% if chunk.is_canonical %}
                <span class="dup__badge">canonical</span>
                {% endif %}
              </div>
              <p class="dup__chunk-preview">{{ chunk.preview }}</p>
            </div>
            {% endfor %}
          </div>
        </article>
        {% endfor %}
      </div>
    </section>
    {% endif %}

    <section class="card">
      <header class="card__header">
        <h2>Top {{ top_files | length }} largest files</h2>
        <p class="card__subtitle">Ranked by total token cost. "Bloat" is the
        share of this file's body that promptc flagged as duplicated with
        another file.</p>
      </header>

      {% if top_files %}
      <table class="files">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="col-rank">#</th>
            <th class="col-path">File</th>
            <th class="col-role">Role</th>
            <th class="col-num" title="Total tokens including frontmatter and body">Tokens</th>
            <th class="col-bloat" title="Share of this file's body that promptc flagged as duplicated with content elsewhere">Bloat</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {% for f in top_files %}
          <tr>
            <td class="col-rank">{{ f.rank }}</td>
            <td class="col-path"><code>{{ f.path }}</code></td>
            <td class="col-role"><span class="role role--{{ f.role }}">{{ f.role }}</span></td>
            <td class="col-num">{{ "{:,}".format(f.total_tokens) }}</td>
            <td class="col-bloat">
              {% if f.duplicate_tokens %}
                <div class="bloat">
                  <div class="bloat__bar">
                    <div class="bloat__fill"
                         style="width: {{ (f.duplicate_ratio * 100) | round(0, 'floor') | int }}%;"></div>
                  </div>
                  <span class="bloat__pct">{{ "{:.0f}%".format(f.duplicate_ratio * 100) }}</span>
                </div>
              {% else %}
                <span class="dim">—</span>
              {% endif %}
            </td>
          </tr>
          {% endfor %}
        </tbody>
      </table>
      {% else %}
      <p class="empty">No files scanned.</p>
      {% endif %}
    </section>

    <section class="card methodology" id="methodology">
      <header class="card__header">
        <h2>How this is graded</h2>
        <p class="card__subtitle">promptc's grades and metrics are heuristics,
        not benchmarks. This section explains exactly how each number above was
        computed, so you can reproduce or contest any of them.</p>
      </header>

      <h3 class="methodology__heading">Efficiency Grade</h3>
      <p>The grade reflects the <strong>duplicate-content ratio</strong>:
      the share of skill-body tokens that promptc flagged as a near-duplicate
      of content elsewhere in the scan.</p>
      <pre class="methodology__formula">bloat_ratio = duplicate_tokens / total_tokens</pre>
      <table class="methodology__rubric">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Grade</th><th>Bloat ratio</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><span class="grade-pill grade-pill--a">A</span></td><td>&lt; 5%</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="grade-pill grade-pill--b">B</span></td><td>5% &mdash; 15%</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="grade-pill grade-pill--c">C</span></td><td>15% &mdash; 25%</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="grade-pill grade-pill--d">D</span></td><td>25% &mdash; 40%</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="grade-pill grade-pill--f">F</span></td><td>&ge; 40%</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Each non-F letter splits into <code>+</code> (lower bloat half of the
      bracket) and <code>-</code> (upper half). F has no modifier.</p>
      <p class="methodology__caveat"><strong>These thresholds are heuristic.</strong>
      They were chosen by intuition before any reference distribution
      existed. v0.2 will replace them with empirical breakpoints derived from
      a corpus of real <code>.claude/</code> directories. Contributions
      welcome — see the project's roadmap.</p>

      <h3 class="methodology__heading">Skill Context Exposure</h3>
      <p>The exposure multiplier measures the ceiling cost if Claude loads
      a skill's full body instead of just its description at session start:</p>
      <pre class="methodology__formula">multiplier = SKILL.md body tokens / description tokens</pre>
      <p>Both numerator and denominator are <em>content tokens</em> —
      frontmatter overhead (delimiters, name, other fields) is excluded from
      both sides, so the ratio is symmetric.</p>
      <p>The behavior we're measuring is described in
      <a href="{{ anthropic_docs_url }}" rel="noopener">Claude Code's Skills
      documentation</a>: descriptions load at startup, full bodies on demand.
      Community reports describe setups where the full body ends up in
      context anyway — see
      <a href="{{ community_issue_url }}" rel="noopener">claude-code#14882</a>.
      promptc makes no claim about whether that happens in your setup; it
      measures the upper bound.</p>

      <h3 class="methodology__heading">Insufficient data</h3>
      <p>The "Not enough to audit yet" hero appears when:</p>
      <ul class="methodology__list">
        <li>fewer than 3 SKILL.md files <strong>OR</strong></li>
        <li>fewer than 1,000 aggregate body tokens across skills</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="methodology__caveat">These thresholds are heuristic too.
      They exist so a single tiny skill, or a few placeholder skills, doesn't
      get a misleading A+. They are not empirically calibrated.</p>

      <h3 class="methodology__heading">Token counts</h3>
      <p>{{ disclaimer }}</p>
      <p class="methodology__caveat">Error magnitude on CJK and code-heavy
      content is unmeasured but expected to be larger than on prose. Run
      <code>scripts/validate_tokenizer.py</code> with an Anthropic API key
      to compare cl100k_base against Claude's <code>count_tokens</code>
      endpoint on your own corpus.</p>
    </section>

  </main>

  <footer class="footer">
    <div class="footer__row">
      <span>Generated by <strong>promptc</strong> v{{ version }}</span>
      <span class="footer__path">{{ scan.root }}</span>
    </div>
  </footer>

</body>
</html>
